data.message: Late night

T’was the night before big game, when all through greek row,
Not a white girl was screaming, not even Chi-O
The beers were stocked in the fridge by the rack
In the hopes that the Bears would soon get a sac.
The students were nestled snug in their beds,
With visions of touchdown dances in their heads.
And in lucky socks, and jerseys and caps
They’d come back from the game for drunken naps
When out of the stadium there rose such a clatter,
I sprang from my bunk to see what was the matter.
To the window, my bros right behind
Tore open the shutters and threw up the blinds
The sun was rising, the speakers were powered
The tailgates were starting, I hopped in the shower.
On with my cal gear, I ran down the stairs
Had pledges hold signs with our parking fares
And on morning went, as game time drew near,
Our bellies were full with pre-game beers
We got to the stadium, took our seats in the stand
Cheered for dancers and mic men, rally-comm and band
With a little old driver, the ball was hiked
I knew in the moment it must be Coach Dykes
More rapid than the Trees, his Bears they came,
And he whistled, and shouted, and called them by name!
Now Webb! Now, Hansen! Now, Stovall and Walker!
On, Robertson! On, Peterson! On, Downs and Garner!
To the Stanfurd Endzone! To the top of the play!
Now pass the ball! Run the ball! Make the fans day!
As Stanfurd Trees fall and hit the ground with a thud
When they come ‘cross the bears, there will be tears and blood
So up to the line the team took the ball,
With the students cheering, watching them all
And then with a whistle, I heard through the crush
The bears sacked Stanfurd in a defensive rush.
As we screamed and hollered and let out a cry,
The bears had stopped Stanfurd from a touchdown drive.
They wore blue and gold, the colors offset
And their jerseys were tarnished with dedication and sweat
The punt they received, and they ran and they passed
And they pushed for our goal, to get the axe back.
Their tackles-how crushing! Their plays- how fast!
They made their drive. Stanfurd they passed.
The receivers ran in a line and a hook
And with a touchdown, another six points they took.
They spoke not a word, and turned straight back around,
With a successful conversion they drove Trees to the ground.
And the crowds they were cheering, as the clock ran down low
And the mic men were screaming and the speakers did blow.
The fourth quarter ended with a blow of a whistle,
And the crowd rushed the field like the down of a thistle.
But I heard them exclaim, as Dykes grabbed the mic back,
“Happy Big Game to All, Now we have the axe.
